ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic degradation (Chen et al., 2018) of the toxic CV dye by photoactive-CD was analyzed by UV–Vis spectra at 589 nm wavelength and Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) spectroscopy. Fig. 3 (a) showing the influence of catalyst on degradation of 20 ppm CV dye solution when exposed to dark (where no visible light is present) and under the sunlight (with and without catalyst) conditions. There was no effect of a catalyst in dark condition but under sunlight, CV dye degradation takes place in ~ 90 min with catalyst. It was observed that ~ 1% CV was adsorbed on the photoactive-CD in an initial 10 min of experiment. Photocatalytic degradation (Costa et al., 2004) of dye was observed by calculating the relative change in concentration of CV with time, along with considerable change in the rate of decolorization. Fig. 3(b) shows plot of C/Co versus time to observe the influence of catalyst on different concentrations of CV dye solutions (20 ppm, 40 ppm, 60 ppm, 80 ppm and 100 ppm) under illumination of sun light for the same time period (90 min.). This dose dependent experiment indicates that on increasing dye concentration, there is an increase in the number of CV molecules which hinders photon to reach photocatalyst, hence resulting in a decrease in rate of photodegradation. Fig. 3(c) is the pseudo-first-order kinetics graph corresponding to CV dye degradation. Fig. 3(d) shows the effect of catalyst loading on the efficiency of dye degradation. The increase in catalyst dosage results in faster degradation process. To find out reactive species responsible for photodegradation of dye by photoactive-CD, trap experiment using various scavengers (Anand et al., 2019) has been performed. Fig. 3(e) is showing the results of trap experiment by using different types of scavengers (Park et al., 2019), where electron and holes seem to be mostly responsible for photocatalytic activity (Mahmoodi et al., 2018). When electrons and holes, gets trapped by Na2-EDTA complex, the rate of photodegradation decreases. Whereas, using other species as trapping agents (Saini et al., 2019) like para-benzoquinone for superoxide and tertiary-butanol for hydroxyl radicals (Nezar and Laoufi, 2018), their effect is less pronounced as compared to electrons-holes. The cartoon illustration of possible mechanism based on the trap experiment is shown in Fig. 3(f) and the reaction involved in the photodegradation mechanism is depicted in Fig. 3(g). According to the results of trap experiment, CV dye molecules were initially interacting with photoactive-CD via functional moieties present on its surface and under the illumination by sunlight, the photoactive-CD get activated. Afterwards, from the activated CD, electron and holes were excited from HOMO (valence band) to LUMO (conduction band) by creating holes in the HOMO, and electron-hole pairs are generated (Eq. (1)). These holes either react with the adsorbed water molecules to create hydroxyl radicals (OH
) (Asl et al., 2019). (Eq. (2)) or directly oxidize CV molecules to organic radicals as CV
(Eq. (3)). Furthermore, the surface adsorbed oxygen molecule or hydroxyl radical as a reactive oxygen species (ROS) interacts with the CV molecule to photo degrade it into smaller molecules/fragments (Eq. (4) & (5)). The recycle study was done by the same experimental procedure as used for CV dye degradation. For recycle study, the solid residue left after photodegradation was collected by centrifugation and washed with distilled water several times followed by drying at ~100 °C (Dasari and Guttena, 2019). The dried photocatalyst was used for the next six cycles in dye photodegradation as shown in Fig. 3(h). For the support of presented photoactive-CD, a comparative literature analysis based on different catalysts for removal of toxic CV dye was summarized in Table 1 .
